ossessed a remarkable body of geographical knowledge in written rather than cartographic form, Howe demonstrates. To understand fully their cultural geography, he considers Anglo-Saxon writings about the places they actually inhabited and those they imagined. He finds in Anglo-Saxon geographic images a persistent sense of being far from the center of the world, and he discusses how these migratory peoples narrowed that distance and developed ways to define themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnglo-Saxons. 0aCivilization, Anglo-Saxon, in literature. 0aCivilization, Anglo-Saxon. 0aCultural geographyzGreat Britain. 0aEnglish literatureyOld English, ca. 450-1100xHistory and criticism. 0aManuscripts, MedievalzEngland. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030011933640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015014840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300150148423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300150148/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY